               <interp inst="t18470301-857" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470301"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470301-857" type="date" value="18470301"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470301-857-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-857-18470301 t18470301-857-offence-1 t18470301-857-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010185"></xptr>
               <p>857. <persName id="def1-857-18470301" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-857-18470301" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-857-18470301" type="age" value="23"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-857-18470301" type="surname" value="CLARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-857-18470301" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN CLARK</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470301-857-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470301-857-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470301-857-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>for stealing 1 half-crown, 14 shillings, and 2 sixpences, the monies of <persName id="t18470301-name-1191" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1191" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1191" type="surname" value="MALONE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1191" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470301-857-offence-1 t18470301-name-1191"></join>Catherine Malone</persName>, from her person.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1192" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1192" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1192" type="surname" value="MALONE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1192" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE MALONE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am single, and live at No. 1, Three Kings-court, Whitecross-court—I have lived there since I left my situation, six or seven weeks ago. I have been acquainted with the prisoner better than twelve months—he proposed to marry me about a month ago—for about two or three months he had never stopped from my place—in consequence of his request, I left my situation, and went to live with my sister—after that he wanted money to furnish him with some clothes, and I let him have it—he imposed on me the belief that he was going to marry me, and I furnished him with money to <hi rend="italic">rig</hi> himself out—he then took me to buy a wedding-ring at my own expense, and then persuaded me to give him money to buy furniture, a table and chairs, and to take a room—he represented that he had collected articles in the room—he asked me for the key of the room to put an article in—I went very early the next morning for it, and could not get it—I found the banns were not put up where he said they were—Tuesday, the 16th of Feb., was fixed on for our marriage—he appointed Mr. Swaine's lodging, near Cripplegate church, to meet me to go to get married—I found him there—in going, as I supposed, to church, when we got to Aldersgate-street we went to a public-house—we had some refreshment, and I changed a sovereign—I had 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in my pocket—I sat down near the prisoner—he asked me to show him what money I had in my pocket—I was not in the act of counting it—I had changed a sovereign, and I had my hand in my pocket, putting the money in—he reached over and snatched my money from my hand—he turned the pocket up, and took every farthing of money—I resisted—I put my hand on his, and said, "You have got every farthing of money I have, and I could take better care of it than you"—he said, "It would look very stupid of me, when we get to church, not to have the money to pay the fees, but to have to ask you for it"—he assigned that as a reason for taking it from me—we got into a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and when got out, he pointed to a church just by, and said, "That is the church"—he took me to another public-house, and then he <hi rend="italic">cut</hi> away through the courts, leaving me to pay the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>,—I had not a farthing, but my sister, who was with me, had a few shillings, or else we should all have been given in charge—I afterwards found the prisoner in Red Lion-court, wearing the coat I had bought for him—I asked him for the ring and the money be <hi rend="italic">thieved</hi> out of my pocket—he said he had lost the ring.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many friends were with you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two, my sister Margaret, and a young English lady, Elizabeth Sperring—they were in the public-house—Mr. Swaine was there—the prisoner was on my left-hand side—I had no one on the other side—the prisoner was not at a distance—my pocket was on my right side, and he put his hand down, and turned out what was in my pocket—Mr. Swaine and Elizabeth Sperring were at other end, and the table between us—there was no one near me and the prisoner—my sister saw what was going on—she was not with the others—Mr. Swaine's back was turned to me—the other young woman and herself saw nothing, but they heard the making mention of a few words—I thought that money would be expended in the marriage fees—the prisoner said he was to give it to the clergyman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he not say he intended to carry the money because he intended to wear the breeches? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I wanted to have the money back, and he said, "What I have I will keep, because I will wear the breeches"—that was after he had got the money—he did not count the money, for he put it into his pocket as soon as he took it.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010186"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Tell us exactly what occurred at the time your money was taken? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> After coming in from the bar I had the money in my hand—I counted it after getting change at the bar—it was all right—I had 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I had part of it in my pocket, and the other in my hand—I took out a sove<lb></lb>reign, to pay for some cold meat, and bread, and porter—I took in my hand what change I had got, and put it into my pocket—when I went in he saw me putting my hand into my pocket, he took hold of my hand, and took what I had in my hand, and what was in my pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> But you have said before, that he asked what money you had got? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, about five minutes before I changed the sovereign he asked what money I had got—I was putting my hand again into my pocket—I had my pocket up, not to make a noise—I let it go willingly, because I thought he would not take what was in my pocket at the bottom, and he took it all—he had got the money from me before he assigned the reason that it was to pay for what was to happen in the church—he got it from me without that explanantion—it was against my consent—I only did not take steps to recover it because I believed at the time what he said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not say on another occasion, that when he asked what money you had got, you said, "I have not much;" he asked you to let him see how much, and you took some of the money out, and was counting it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He asked five minutes before, had I much money—I said, "I must look sharp, I have not much money now, scarcely as much as will free us from the Church"—I was not counting it—I did not say I was counting it when he took it out of my hand—I was counting it at the bar, and I was looking at it to see if it was right—as I came from the bar I was putting it into my pocket, and he thrust his hand across, and took hold of it—I did not intend to part with my money to him when he took it, but he quieted me by telling me it would be spent in the Church—he took it without my consent.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1193" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1193" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1193" type="surname" value="MALONE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1193" type="given" value="MARGARET"></interp>MARGARET MALONE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the sister of Catherine Malone. I was at the public-house in Aldersgate-street with them—I was standing by the side of the table—the prisoner was sitting by my sister's side—he ate his breakfast—my sister had one knee on the top of the other—the prisoner put his hand in her pocket, took up the money, and put it in his own pocket—she made an attempt to take the money out of his hand—she got him by the two hands and tried to get it—he put it into his pocket, and said he should wear the breeches—I went with them to Lambeth—there was a church at the side of the street, and a public-house at the other side—he stopped the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> man at the public-house—we got out of the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>—he pointed and said, "That is the Church"—he went into the public-house and called for half-a-pint of rum—I followed him and brought him out by the body—the publican asked what out intention was—I said they were going to be married, and he said, "You have not many minutes to delay"—it was only ten minutes to twelve o'clock—the prisoner said, "Where is <hi rend="italic">Kitty</hi>?—I said, "There she is"—he followed her up, and between her and me he ran away—he had got all my sister's money, and goods, and everything else—she had not a farthing left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In the public-house did you not hear the prisoner whisper to her, and then take the money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—he did not like her well enough to whisper—I never saw a young man that had such a dislike to a young woman in company—he did not whisper before he put his hand in her pocket—this is my mark to this deposition—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>—"On the day they were going to be married I went with them to the public-house in Alders<lb></lb>gate-street—the prisoner whispered to her, and then put his hand down to her pocket."</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010187"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Why do you tell us now that he did not whisper to her when you said before the Magistrate that he did whisper to her? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, his head was quite close to her ear—I did not hear it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Now you recollect there was some whispering? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I did not see my sister counting the money—I heard her say, "Let me have my money."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1194" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1194" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1194" type="surname" value="WREFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1194" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WREFORD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable No.</hi> 54.) I was called by Margaret Malone to a house in Red Lion-court, Fleet-street—I there re<lb></lb>ceived the prisoner in charge—I heard the prosecutrix ask him where the ring was—he said it was lost.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1195" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1195" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1195" type="surname" value="ROOTS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1195" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>JONATHAN ROOTS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the parish clerk of Spitalfields. I register the banns of marriage at that Church—no banns have been put up between the prisoner and Catherine Malone.</p>
               <p>----<hi rend="smallCaps">BIRKET</hi>. I register the banns of marriage at the parish Church of St. Giles, Cripplegate—no banns have been put up there for a marriage be<lb></lb>tween the prisoner and Catherine Malone.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How do you know that? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have referred to the book, and have no such name for three months back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1196" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1196" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1196" type="surname" value="GOWRIE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1196" type="given" value="JAMES MARTIN"></interp>JAMES MARTIN GOWRIE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am parish clerk of St. Mary's, Lambeth. We have no register of the banns of the prisoner and Catherine Malone—we have no such names for the last three months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1197" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1197" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1197" type="surname" value="SWAINE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1197" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE SWAINE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a dress-maker. I was present at the public-house when these parties were going to be married—it was at the King's Arms, in Aldersgate-street—I saw some money pass between them—I sat directly opposite Catherine and John Clarke—I saw the prosecutrix count money into his hand—he sat on the left side of her—her pocket was on the right—I made her dress—I saw her take the money out of her pocket and count it into his hand—that was not many minutes before we left—we got up directly and proceeded to Lambeth—Catherine proposed having a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and two females sat inside.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you get to the King's Arms? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think it must have been about eleven o'clock—they started from my house—when they got to the King's Arms they had a Knuckle of harm or bacon—Catherine went outside, and paid for what we had—when she came back she sat down, and the prisoner sat on the left-hand side of her—they were talking, but I was not close enough to hear their conversation—I was opposite them, but the table was between us, and it was lengthways—I saw her put her hand into her pocket, take out the money, and count it into his hand—I do not know what money she counted—her friend was sitting by my side, addressing herself to me, which took my attention—I saw her count it into his hand—I know there were half-crowns—I saw that—this was done voluntarily; in fact she was smiling the whole time—she never demanded it back—I believe the word did pass that he would wear the breeches—she made no effort to get the money back—she gave it him deliberately—he and her were talking at the bar afterwards, and I thought he had given her the money back—I do not know what he did with it—I did not see him put it into his pocket—we all got up—I heard Catherine say, "Come, John, we shall be too late."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see them speak? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—they were talk<lb></lb>ing the whole time after they has eaten—I did not hear them talk loud in a rational manner—Elizabeth Sperring was talking to me—I could not listen to both at once—Margaret Malone was standing in the middle of the floor—I did not feel much interest in their conversation.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010188"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1198" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1198" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1198" type="surname" value="SPERRING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1198" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH SPERRING</persName>
                  </hi>. I was in the King's Arms, Aldersgate-street—we left Mr. Swaine's in Red Cross-street, and went there to wait for Mr. Swaine—the prisoner said he was rather hungry—Catherine went out to get some provision at the bar—she came in and sat down—it was a long table—the prisoner sat down opposite her, and eat up the refreshment—the bride sat opposite him, not by the side of him—after the refreshment Mr. Swaine came in—the prisoner got up, gave him his seat, and he went and sat on the left side of Catherine—Mr. Swaine and I were at the other end—Margaret Malone was standing up—I never saw any money, nor heard it—I never saw the money pass either way—the only word I heard was, "I shall wear the breeches"—I do not know on what subject the prisoner used those words—Mr. Swaine did not see what took place—when we got into the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> Catherine said, "He has got all my money"—I told it to Mr. Swaine—"Oh dear!" (she said) "has he got her money?"—she said it as if she were surprised, not as if she had seen it counted into his hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18470301-857-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
